-- BHP, Boral, CSR, Lihir, Rio, Telstra, Woodside: Australian Stock Preview
-- Shani Raja
-- 2010-06-27T22:18:41Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-27/bhp-boral-csr-lihir-rio-telstra-woodside-australian-stock-preview.html

          
          
             The following is a list of companies
whose shares may rise or fall in Australia. This preview
includes news announced after markets closed on June 25. All
prices are from that day’s close unless otherwise stated.  
 The S&P/ASX 200 Index  futures contract  due in Sept. slipped
0.1 percent to 4,414 as of 6:58 a.m. in Sydney. The  Bank of New
York Australia ADR Index  gained 0.4 percent. The  S&P/ASX 200
Index  declined 1.5 percent to 4,413.  
 Mining shares: Copper futures for September delivery
climbed 2.9 percent to $3.111 a pound on the Comex in New York.  
 BHP Billiton  (BHP AU), the world’s largest mining company,
lost 2.1 percent to A$38.80 in Sydney. Its American depositary
receipts were little changed in New York trading.  
 Rio Tinto Group (RIO AU), the world’s third-largest mining
company, retreated 3 percent to A$69.60 in Sydney. The company
said it has been in contact with Australia’s new Prime Minister
 Julia Gillard  about a proposed mining tax and will negotiate
further.  
 Oil companies: Crude oil for August delivery increased 3.1
percent to settle at $78.86 a barrel on the New York Mercantile
Exchange. It was the biggest gain since June 9.  
 Woodside Petroleum Ltd.  (WPL AU), Australia’s second-
largest oil and gas producer, dropped 2.9 percent to A$43.28,
and rival Santos Ltd. (STO AU) fell 0.9 percent to A$12.70.  
 Gold producers: Gold rose for a second day in New York,
gaining 0.8 percent to $1,256.20 an ounce on the Comex.  
 Newcrest Mining Ltd.  (NCM AU), Australia’s biggest gold
producer, climbed 1 percent to A$36.  Lihir Gold Ltd.  (LGL AU),
the second-largest gold producer on the Australian stock
exchange, gained 1.6 percent to A$4.44.  
      Boral Ltd.  (BLD AU): Boral may seek to sell units, cut
staff and expand into faster-growing regions such as Asia as
part of a new business strategy, the Australian Financial Review
reported, without saying where it got the information. Boral
shares were unchanged at A$5.06.  
      CSR Ltd.  (CSR AU): Australia’s second-largest building-
products maker may receive a formal bid from Bright Food Group
Co. for its sugar unit before CSR’s annual general meeting on
July 8, the Australian Financial Review reported, without saying
where it got the information. CSR shares dipped 0.9 percent to
A$1.72.  
      Telstra Corp.  (TLS AU): Australia’s largest telephone
company may consider acquisitions to bolster growth after
reaching agreement with the government’s NBN Co. on the closure
of its copper-wire network, Chief Executive Officer  David Thodey 
said in an Australian Broadcasting Corp. interview. Telstra
shares fell 1.2 percent to A$3.30.  
